% \begin{align}
\includegraphics[scale=1.5]{circle.svg} \end{align} %text A circle is the locus of all points that are equi-distant from a given point (known as the center) The figure above shows a circle whose center is at the origin $O$ It does not have to be though. The center can be at any point $(a,b)$ The \underline\text{standard equation} of a circle with center at $(a,b)$ and radius $R$ is \[ \qquad \left(x-a \right)^2 + \left(y-b \right)^2 = R^2 \] When the center is at the origin, that is $(a,b) = (0,0)$, then this boils down to \[ \qquad x^2 + y^2 = R^2 \] %
